{"cards":[{"lines":[{"type":"title","text":"Strong force"},{"type":"headline","text":"Holds particles in nucleus together"},{"type":"headline","text":"Is very strong!"},{"type":"headline","text":"Always attractive, regardless of charge"},{"type":"headline","text":"Acts only over a very short range"}]},{"lines":[{"type":"title","text":"Stable nuclei"},{"type":"headline","text":"Stable only for certain combinations of neutrons and protons"}]}],"definitions":[],"secText":["  <b>Essential Question: <\/b>  <b>    <br \/>  <\/b>How can we explain the stability of the nucleus?","  <b>Enduring Understandings:<\/b>  <b>    <br \/>  <\/b>1. There are four fundamental forces. The <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='22' data-topic='1' data-subtopic='1' data-subsection='0'>gravitational force<\/a> is the force that attracts two masses to each other. The <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='22' data-topic='1' data-subtopic='1' data-subsection='0'>electromagnetic force<\/a> is the force between two charged particles or on a charge moving in a magnetic field. The <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='22' data-topic='1' data-subtopic='1' data-subsection='1'>strong force<\/a> holds the nucleus together by attracting protons and neutrons to each other. The <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='22' data-topic='1' data-subtopic='1' data-subsection='1'>weak force<\/a> allows the neutron to divide into neutrinos, electrons, and protons.<br \/>2. A nucleus is <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='22' data-topic='1' data-subtopic='2' data-subsection='0'>stable<\/a> when it does not spontaneously decay. An <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='22' data-topic='1' data-subtopic='2' data-subsection='0'>unstable<\/a> element decays into more stable elements.<br \/>3. The <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='22' data-topic='1' data-subtopic='3' data-subsection='0'>energy of an object<\/a> at rest is equal to its mass multiplied by the speed of light squared.","  <b>Vocabulary:<\/b>  <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='22' data-topic='1' data-subtopic='1' data-subsection='1'>strong force<\/a>, <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='22' data-topic='1' data-subtopic='1' data-subsection='1'>weak force<\/a>, <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='22' data-topic='1' data-subtopic='2' data-subsection='0'>stable<\/a>, <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='22' data-topic='1' data-subtopic='2' data-subsection='0'>unstable<\/a>, <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='22' data-topic='1' data-subtopic='2' data-subsection='1'>nuclide<\/a>, <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='22' data-topic='1' data-subtopic='2' data-subsection='2'>binding energy<\/a>","  <b>STEM Skills:<\/b>  <b>    <br \/>  <\/b>1. Review the <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='8' data-topic='2' data-subtopic='1' data-subsection='1'>gravitational force<\/a>.<br \/>2. Review the <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='17' data-topic='0' data-subtopic='3' data-subsection='3'>electromagnetic force<\/a>.<br \/>3. Review <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='15' data-topic='0' data-subtopic='1' data-subsection='1'>electrons and protons<\/a>."],"objNames":["wb_strong_force_concepts","wb_stable_nuclei_concepts"]}